<text top="252" left="105" width="324" height="15" font="0">Just out of graduate school I would meticulously</text>
<text top="270" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">write down every word that I wanted to say in as-</text>
<text top="288" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">sociation with the talk. I would practice, and prac-</text>
<text top="306" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">tice, and practice, then throw the notes away to actu-</text>
<text top="324" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">ally give the talk. I still occasionally do this. Why?</text>
<text top="341" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">With a limited time frame, and under the glare of</text>
<text top="359" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">my colleagues, making language precise helps get</text>
<text top="377" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">the message across, which is respectful of the audi-</text>
<text top="395" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">ence. Making the notes makes the language precise,</text>
<text top="413" left="82" width="340" height="15" font="0">but giving the talk without notes lends spontaneity.</text>
<text top="432" left="105" width="324" height="15" font="0">Check the equipment. How does your font and</text>
<text top="450" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">the graphics appear from the back of the room? Does</text>
<text top="468" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">your computer work with the projector? Or does the</text>
<text top="486" left="82" width="346" height="15" font="0">provided computer have the software that you need</text>
<text top="504" left="82" width="147" height="15" font="0">for your presentation?</text>
